      "web_research": {
        "results": [
          {
            "possibleIdentity": "Lillian Feldman Schwartz (1927–2024) was an American artist and a seminal pioneer in computer-mediated art, kinetic sculpture, and digital filmmaking. Active primarily from the late 1960s through the 1970s and beyond, she was an early member of the Experiments in Art and Technology (E.A.T.) group, joining in 1966. Her breakthrough came in 1968 with her kinetic sculpture 'Proxima Centauri', which was featured in the Museum of Modern Art's influential exhibition 'The Machine as Seen at the End of the Mechanical Age'. This sculpture also gained pop-culture fame as a prop in the original 'Star Trek' series. In 1968, she began a 34-year tenure as a resident visitor at AT&T Bell Laboratories, where she collaborated with engineers and scientists like Leon Harmon and Kenneth Knowlton. During this period, she created some of the first digitally animated films, including 'Pixillation' (1970), 'UFOs' (1971), 'Enigma' (1972), and 'Googolplex' (1972), often using the BEFLIX programming language. Schwartz is also famous for her 'Mona/Leo' study, which used computer analysis to suggest a structural alignment between Leonardo da Vinci's self-portrait and the Mona Lisa. Her work is held in major collections such as MoMA and the Whitney Museum of American Art, and her archive is preserved at The Henry Ford Museum.",
